<br>
I think I would fall into that third category because from what I've heard from both the calvinistic and arminian doctrines, I don't fully agree with either.  There are parts of each I agree with, but I seem to fall somewhere in the middle, even though calvinists try to tell me it's impossible.  It's possible, I know me better than they know me. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
One thing I guess I don't like so much about the calvinistic approach is that they seem to be solely trying to explain everything from God's perspective and it seems to me, we're a bit small to be able to understand God's perspective.  We ourselves have a very human perspective on things.  And I don't think He has revealed as much to us as calvinists seem to think He has.<br>
<br>
I believe in a predestination because the Bible says that word very clearly.  But I don't think we can fully understand what that means exactly.  Because the Bible tells us that the foolishness of God is wiser than man's wisdom.  That means out best wisdom is more foolish than God's foolishness.  So I think at some point we should be willing to admit we don't know everything and accept by faith that one day God will answer all our questions, some in this life and some and the rest in the life to come.  I believe God predestined us to have a choice because the Bible does say, &quot;Choose today whom you will serve.&quot; <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
